Numerous reptiles that are either endangered, threatened or species of concern live within the Highlands. The Timber Rattlesnake (Crotalus horidus) is the only snake that is on the state endangered list (threatened in New York) and on of the most vulnerable of all endangered species.

Moreover, forests provide habitat to plants and animals, and preserve biodiversity. The New Jersey Highlands have exceptionally diverse natural communities. Black bear, river otters, bobcat and wild trout make their homes in the region, as do many other species of mammals, fish, amphibians and reptiles.

Seventy-two New Jersey-listed endangered, threatened and rare animal species live in the New Jersey Highlands, including mammals, birds, amphibians, reptiles, butterflies, dragonflies, damselflies and mussels. Three species — the Indiana bat, bog turtle, and bald eagle — are Federally-listed.
